stix:Indicator.indicator:Title: CYT3: FS-ISAC Technical Analysis Report: DBGer Ransomware - A New Variant of Satan Ransomware (Tracking ID: 940727)
stix:Indicator.indicator:Description:
The FS-ISAC Technical Analysis Report (TAR) provides consolidated technical analysis on a specific topic to assist members sifting through the dozens of emails they receive every day. It speaks purely from a technical research point of view.
Satan ransomware was first discovered by security researchers in early 2017 and has since quickly gained notoriety as a relatively polished ransomware-as-a-service (RaaS) operation. Rather than distributing the ransomware solely themselves, the developers behind Satan have made the source code freely available to anyone who is eager to get in on the ransomware market. Prospective users must sign up and Satan developers provide them with everything they need to start launching custom ransomware campaigns. Because the launch of Satan and other ransomware-as-a-service (RaaS) platforms is rapidly lowering the entry level barrier for cyber criminals.
According to researchers at MalwareHunterTeam, the developers of Satan have rebranded their product to the name of DBGer ransomware. The change is not only in the name but also in the ransomware's modus operandi. This new variant, DBGer ransomware, is using the EternalBlue exploit as well as Mimikatz, an open-source password-dumping utility. These are similar exploits associated with the previous WannaCry and NotPetya Ransomware campaigns.
DBGer ransomware encrypts most stored files and renames them using the "[dbger[@]protonmail[.]com][original_filename].dbger" pattern. For example, "sample.jpg" is renamed to "[dbger[@]protonmail[.]com]sample.jpg.dbger". The compromised data immediately becomes unusable. Following successful encryption, DBGer generates a text file ("_How_to_decrypt_files.txt") and opens it automatically. As usual, the new text file contains a message informing the victim about the encryption. Victims are encouraged to pay a ransom to restore the data. The message is delivered in three languages: English, Korean, and Chinese. Therefore, it is safe to assume the developers are from Asia or target users who live in this region. It is currently unknown which cryptographic algorithm (asymmetric or asymmetric) DBGer uses although the decryption requires a unique key. Developers of DBGer store all keys on a remote server. Victims are encouraged to pay a ransom of 1 Bitcoin (currently equivalent to ~$6100) to receive the decryption key. It is also stated that ransoms must be paid within three days after encryption, otherwise restoring compromised data is no longer possible. Note that, as compared to other ransomware-type attacks, this cost is extremely high (ransoms typically fluctuate between $500 and $1500).
Keypoints: DBGer ransomware uses EternalBlue to scan the local network for computers with outdated SMB services and infects them as well. EternalBlue was previously used in WannaCry, NotPetya, and UIWIX ransomware campaigns. Along with several known CVE exploits, DBGer ransomware drops Mimikatz to dump passwords for networked computers and using these credentials to access and infect those devices as well. DBGer is featured with self-spreading mechanisms and as a move to infect larger networks instead of home users.
